[2
Date: Tue 1 May 2001 19:34:53 +0800
From: Dr. K.H. Sng <mei@pc.jaring.my>
In Malaysia, I had the privilege of looking after 14 cases of Buruli ulcer,
all of which came from an Orang Asli (aboriginal race) village of Kelubi in
Perak. The lesions and natural history of my patients, jointly managed with
Dr John Petit, consultant dermatologist, were similar to those reported in
Buruli and Queensland.
Resection of the pre-ulcerating nodule was curative. The sites of these
nodules suggest trauma as an important factor, with the soil and grass
(lalang) being possible reservoir.
Local therapy with cleaning and toilet under the deeply undermining ulcers
(typical of mycobacterium lesions) was essential. Also, because _M.
ulcerans_ proliferates best in subnormal body temperature, the hot box
therapy was used for limbs such as elbow and forearm.
We did not find it highly contagious. These are only empirical observations.
--
Dr KH Sng FRCP
<mei@pc.jaring.my>
[The message from Dr. Corbin provides insight into the amount and type of
diagnostic information that provided the background for the article posted
as the first message of this thread. There does not appear to have been a
bacteriological diagnosis for some or all of the cases, but a follow-up
message from Dr. Corbin is invited if he is able to glean any further
information. It appears that the infections reported may have been
diagnosed as _Mycobacterium ulcerans_ based largely upon clinical
observations, but the observations reported are not entirely consistent
with the expected presentation. We would welcome further information if it
becomes available.
The second part of this posting provides an additional indication that
those with experience treating such infections have reason to doubt that
what was described represents a mycobacteriosis. - Mod.ES
